text: : , ; ) ( 0 9 8 7 6 5 4 3 2 1 : , ; ) ( 0 9 8 7 6 5 4 3 2 1 The Journal of Antibiotics https://doi.org/10.1038/s41429-019-0267-8 An aberrant metabolic ﬂow toward early shunt products in the granaticin biosynthetic machinery of Streptomyces vietnamensis GIMV4.0001 Ming-Rong Deng 1 ● Yan Li1 ● Huang-Huang He1 ● Xiaoli Zhou1 ● Xiang-Ling Zheng1 ● Yong-Hong Wang1 ● Honghui Zhu 1 Received: 13 August 2019 / Revised: 15 November 2019 / Accepted: 28 November 2019 © The Author(s), under exclusive licence to the Japan Antibiotics Research Association 2020 Abstract A systematic study of the secondary metabolites of the wild granaticin-producing strain Streptomyces vietnamensis GIMV4.0001 led to the isolation of six known early shunt products related to actinorhodin, SEK34 (3), SEK34b (4), mutactin (5), dehydromutactin (7), EM18 (8) and GTRI-02 (9). While the other shunt products were minor or trace products, the production ratio of SEK34 (3) and SEK34b (4) to granaticins was strikingly high. Nearly 64% of the intermediate with the ﬁrst ring closed went to the SEK34/SEK34b aberrant pathway. The high level of the aberrant metabolic ﬂow toward the early shunt products SEK34 and SEK34b indicated that the second ring closure of the granaticin (1) biosynthesis is a key limiting step in the granaticin biosynthetic machinery of S. vietnamensis GIMV4.0001.

Aromatic polyketides are biosynthesized by type II poly- ketide (PKS) pathways. Such biosynthetic machineries are so efﬁcient that the end products of the pathways are usually the predominant products. Although the nascent polyketide chains are extremely reactive and prone to spontaneous cyclization [1], the early shunt pro- ducts were only occasionally isolated as minor or trace compounds in wild producing strains [2–4]. Instead, most of the early shunt products were originally isolated from engineered Streptoymces strains, which have been sum- marized by Sir David Hopwood [5]. Streptomyces vietnamensis GIMV4.0001 is a new streptomycete species designated by our laboratory [6]. This strain was found to be a new granaticin (1) producer Supplementary information The online version of this article (https:// doi.org/10.1038/s41429-019-0267-8) contains supplementary material, which is available to authorized users. B R I E F C O M M U N I C A T I O N State Key Laboratory of Applied Microbiology Southern China, Guangdong Provincial Key Laboratory of Microbial Culture Collection and Application, Guangdong Microbial Culture Collection Center (GDMCC), Guangdong Institute of Microbiology, Guangdong Academy of Sciences, Guangzhou 510070, People’s Republic of China with granaticin (1) and granaticin B (2) as the pre- dominant products [7]. More recently, we demonstrated that GIMV4.0001 is a genetically amenable strain [8], which could facilitate the studies of the granaticin (1) biosynthesis. Here we report the high ratio production of early shunt products from the granaticin (1) pathway of the wild strain GIMV4.0001 under the optimized granaticin-production conditions, depicting a character- istic aberrant metabolic ﬂow toward early shunt products in the granaticin biosynthetic machinery of S. vietna- mensis GIMV4.0001.

A metabolic proﬁling of GIMV4.0001 revealed the presence of two other major peaks, the UV spectra of which were strikingly distinct from those of the granati- cins. A batch of 20-l liquid culture of GIMV4.0001 was fermented under optimized conditions for 7 days and then was extracted by ethyl acetate (see experimental section in the Supplementary information for details). The crude extract was subjected to silica gel column chromatography and the high performance liquid chromatography. Besides granaticin (1), granaticin B (2) and dihydrogranaticin B (6), compounds 3, 4, 5, 7, 8, and 9 were obtained in amounts of 822, 986, 26, 18, 5 and 6 mg, respectively. By NMR spectroscopy, high resolution mass spectrometry and by comparison with related structures [9–14], the chemical structures of the isolated compounds were determined as SEK34 (3), SEK34b (4), mutactin (5) Fig. 1 Simpliﬁed granaticin biosynthetic pathway and its early shunt products. The percentage shows how much of the intermediate goes to either the normal grantaticin (1) pathway or the aberrant pathway dehydromutactin (7), EM18 (8) and GTRI-02 (9), respectively (Fig. 1, supplementary information for the detailed NMR data).

Surprisingly, all the newly isolated compounds are early shunt products. GTRI-02 (9) was originally isolated from a Micromonospora strain with lipid peroxidation inhibiting activity [14]. Recently, GTRI-02 (9) was found that it is actually a previously unidentiﬁed product of the acti- norhodin pathway in Streptomyces coelicolor A3(2) [15]. The absence of GTRI-02 (9) in the DMR1 mutant in which the minimal PKS genes (gra-orf1, gra-orf2, and gra-orf3) of granaticin (1) were replaced by an aac(3)-IV/oriT cassette [4] strongly suggested that the granaticin (1) gene cluster is responsible for this product (Fig. S1). Several other Strep- tomyces strains were also found to be capable to produce GTRI-02 (9) [16–18], at least one of which was found to leading to SEK34 (3) and SEK34b (4) production. KR ketoreductase, ARO aromatase hold an act-like gene cluster responsible for GTRI-02 (9) [18]. These facts indicate that GTRI-02 (9) might be a common early aberrant product among the octaketide syn- thase pathways. The possible biosynthetic pathway for GTRI-02 (9) has been proposed [15], but the exact pathway still remains elusive.

SEK34 (3) and SEK34b (4) were ﬁrst reported in a recombinant S. coelicolor strain that contains the minimal PKS genes (actI-ORF1, actI-ORF2, and actI-ORF3), actIII (ketoreductase, KR) and actVII (aromatase, ARO) from the actinorhodin pathway [9]. SEK34b (4) was believed to be formed via a spontaneous dehydration of SEK34 (3). In the case of the granaticin (1) biosynthesis, SEK34 (3) could be reasoned to be formed similarly after the aromatization of the ﬁrst ring and before the proper the cyclization of the second ring. The product of An aberrant metabolic ﬂow toward early shunt products in the granaticin biosynthetic machinery of. . .

gra-orf33 gene was predicted to catalyze the second ring cyclization of granaticin (1) [19]. Its counterpart in the actinorhodin pathway, actIV, was recently found to be a bifunctional cyclase‐thioesterase, which catalyzes both the second ring formation and the thioester hydrolysis leading to the release of the bicyclic intermediate from the acyl carrier protein [20]. The large amounts of SEK34 (3) and SEK34b (4) detected in the wild granaticin-producing strain indicated that the catalytic efﬁciency of Gra-ORF33 is insufﬁcient to rapidly convert its substrate into down- stream products in the granaticin (1) biosynthesis. Just recently, an interesting granaticin (1) analog, sek- granaticin, has been identiﬁed [21]. This novel analog was proposed to be product of the conjugation of granaticin (1) and SEK34b (4) [21]. Though the co-existence of grana- ticin (1) and SEK34b (4) in large quantity in our culture system, neither was sekgranaticin detected in the fresh isolated from the large-batch fer- extracts, nor was it mentation. That sekgranaticin is an artiﬁcial or a true natural product remains unknown.

Mutactin (5) and EM18 (8) are closely related shunt products. During the puriﬁcation process, both mutac- tin (5) and EM18 (8) were found to be spontaneously dehydrated into dehydromutactin (7) in which the tetra- lone moiety was rearranged into a substituted naphthalene ring system. Mutactin (5) was ﬁrst reported in an actVII mutant of S. coelicolor [10], while EM18 (8) was ori- ginally isolated from engineered S. coelicolor strains containing hybrid PKS component genes [13]. The fact that both the actVII mutant [10] of S. coelicolor and the engineered strain [12] carrying the combination of the minimal PKS and KR genes could produce mutactin (5), clearly showed that the actVII gene is not necessary for mutactin (5) formation. However, to produce EM18 (8), an ARO gene (whiE-ORFVI) from the spore pigment cluster of S. coelicolor was needed, in addition to the minimal PKS and KR genes. The ability to produce EM18 (8) remained even when the minimal PKS genes were replaced by their counterparts from the frenolicin cluster. The production of EM18 (8) was speculated as a result of the unclear special catalytic properties of the whiE-ORFVI aromatase [13]. The isolation of EM18 (8) from the wild granaticin-producing strain has raised an interesting question: how is it produced? Though it cannot be con- cluded that the isolated EM18 (8) comes from the single pathway of granaticin (1), the failure of detection of EM18 (8) in the DMR1 mutant suggested that the gran- aticin (1) pathway is, at least, partially responsible for production of EM18 (8) (Fig. S1). However, whether it results from the granaticin (1) single pathway or crosstalk of the granaticin (1) pathway with other similar type II polyketide pathway, such as the spore pigment pathway of S. vietnamensis, remains to be further investigated.

The antimicrobial assay was carried out since the antimicrobial activities of some of the isolated compounds have never been reported. However, GTRI-02 (9) had no activity against all the tested strains (the tested strains listed in the experimental section of the supplementary information), while SEK34 (3), SEK34b (4), mutactin (5), dehydromutactin (7) and EM18 (8) only showed very weak activities against Bacillus subtilis ATCC 6633 (Fig. S2). To better understand the dynamic metabolic proﬁles of the granaticin (1) pathway under the lab-controlled condi- tion, a time-course metabolic proﬁling experiment was carried out. Granaticin (1), granaticin B (2) and SEK34 (3) could be detected at day 1. In addition to these compounds, dihydrogranaticin B (6) and all the other compounds emerged at day 2. While other shunt products were accu- mulated slowly, SEK34 (3) was rapidly produced in large quantity at the early stage of fermentation, compared with granaticin (1) and granaticin B (2). Then it was converted into its dehydrated analog, SEK34b (4), at the late stage of fermentation, indicating that the spontaneous dehydration of SEK34 (3) could easily take place under the fermentation condition (Fig. 2).

To further depict the metabolic ﬂuxes of the granaticin (1) pathway, the two major shunt products, SK34 (3) and SEK34b (4), together with granaticin (1) and granaticin B (2) were quantitatively analyzed on a time-course base. The standard curves were generated using puriﬁed compounds (Fig. S3). The highest titers of SK34 (3), SEK34b (4), granaticin (1) and granaticin B (2) were 0.472, 0.424, 0.097, 0.339 µmol ml−1, respectively (Table S1). The overall yield of the four compounds reached the highest level at day 5 the ﬁrst-ring closed intermediate with nearly 64% of undergoing the aberrant cyclization leading to production of SEK34 (3) and SEK34b (4) (Fig. 1). The high ratio pro- duction of SEK34 (3) and SEK34b (4) suggested that, after the ﬁrst-ring aromatization, the intermediate went through an insufﬁcient bicyclic intermediate reaction and this reac- tion is a key limiting step for the granaticin (1) biosynthesis. The minimal PKS is responsible for the linear polyketide biosynthesis. The ketosynthase (KS) and its close partner, the chain length factor (CLF), form a heterodimer in which an amphipathic polyketide tunnel is built at the contacting interface. The growing polyketide chain extrudes into this tunnel, to avoid spontaneous cyclization, where the ketide groups probably contact KS-CLF as enols [22]. In the case of actinorhodin, the ﬁnal condensation to form the octake- tide chain intrigues the ﬁrst ring cyclization between C7 and C12 because the polyketide tunnel does not have enough room to accommodate the nascent octaketide and then the chain is buckled, allowing an intramolecular attack at C7. It was believed that a water molecule which is bound to the backbone amides of Trp135 and Phe136 of CLF participates

To get some clues for the possible mechanism for this characteristic aberrant ﬂux, homology models of the Gra-ORF1 (KS) and Gra-ORF2 (CLF) proteins from both S. vietnamensis GIMV4.0001 and Streptomyces violaceoruber Tü22 were constructed using the structure of actinorhodin KS-CLF (PDB entry: 1tqy) as template (Fig. S4). One of the key residues bound to the catalytic water molecule, Trp135, is conserved in acti- norhodin CLF and the Gra-ORF2 of S. violaceoruber Tü22. the corresponding residue was found to be Whereas, in the Gra-ORF2 of replaced by a leucine (Leu149) GIMV4.0001. Relative to the large aromatic side chain of Trp, the smaller aliphatic side chain of leucine makes the polyketide tunnel of GIMV4.0001 more spacious than that of Tü22, which may allow the ketone ester side chain of the proposed one-ring intermediate more swaying and thus increase the possibility that the upper side chain (C13–C16) fuses into the ﬁrst ring from another direction during releasing from the KS-CLF heterodimer.

Another possibility lies on the cyclase gene (gra-orf33) itself. As reported previously [7], the organizations of the granaticin clusters from S. vietnamensis GIMV4.0001 and S. violaceoruber Tü22 are same, except for missing of gra-orf35 in GIMV4.0001, which is considered irrelevant to granaticin biosynthesis (Fig. S5a). The overall homol- ogy between these two granaticin clusters was relatively high but varied from gene to gene. The Gra-ORF33 of GIMV4.0001 shared an 89% sequence identity with, but 15 residues shorter at the very beginning of the N end than its equivalent in Tü22 (Fig. S5b). Shorter length may cause less effective in catalysis and, in consequence, lar- ger portion of the proposed one-ring intermediate goes to the aberrant pathway toward SEK34/SEK34b. efﬁciency of gra-orf33 between GIMV4.0001 and Tü22 might also contribute. The intergenic region between gra- orf32 and gra-orf33 of GIMV4.0001 is, in contrast to 43 bp in Tü22, only 19-bp long, which can hardly bear a promotor. An online promoter prediction tool Promo- (http://www.phisite.org/main/index.php?nav= terHunter tools&nav_sel=hunter) was used to predict the possible promoters for the intergenic region between gra-orf32 and gra-orf33. Although, like that of Tü22, two promoters were predicted for GIMV4.0001, the transcription poten- tials are notably different (Fig. S6). In the case of Tü22, one of the predicted promoters locates fully upstream a possible ribosomal binding site and the coding region of gra-orf33 and thus may function virtually. However, both the predicted promoters for GIMV4.0001 overlap with the open reading frame of gra-orf33 itself, which could make the transcripts dysfunctional. Another possible transcrip- tion pattern of gra-orf33 in GIMV4.0001 is co- transcription with the upstream gra-orf32 gene whose function remains elusive but the transcription level of which has never be compared with that of gra-orf33. In summary, we described an aberrant metabolic ﬂow toward SEK34 (3) and SEK34b (4) in the granaticin bio- synthetic machinery of S. vietnamensis GIMV4.0001, which indicated that the cyclization of the second ring is a key limiting step for the granaticin (1) biosynthesis in this strain.
